To estimate the detection limit of Hg2+ by CQDs are examined the fluorescence intensity of CQDs by adding various concentrations of Hg2+ from 0 − 500 µM as illustrated in Fig. 7(c). The CQD fluorescence intensity is diminished significantly with the increased concentration of Hg2+, which denotes that the CQD fluorescence intensity is sensitive to the Hg2+ ion concentration. Fluorescence intensity diminished in direct proportion to Hg2+ concentration [28,55]. The CQDs are noticeably quenched when the Hg2+ concentration is augmented up to 500 µM, with just 43.01 % of the fluorescence intensity remaining compared to the initial intensity. Fig. 7(d) represents the plot of PL intensity vs Hg2+ concentration. A good linear correlation (R2 ∼ 0.996) is exposed underneath the concentration array from 0 to 500 μM. The limit of detection (LOD) is assessed to be 6.2 nM based on three times the standard deviation rule (LOD = 3Sd/s) [56–58]. It must be observed that the CQDs probeacquired detection limits of Hg2+ detection is significantly lower than that of previous reports (Table 2
                        ). The above results specify that our CQDs sensor module exceeds the earlier described sensing probesin terms of sensitivity and that the devices that rely on CQDs might be beneficial in ecological applications for the detection of Hg2+ 
                        [59,60].
